---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

export const prerender = true;
---

<BaseLayout
    title="About"
    description="Dr Fazeen Nasser is an emergency medicine clinician in East London who builds clinical AI products. Everything he's built started as a problem on shift."
>
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 pt-12 pb-16 md:pt-20 md:pb-24">
        <!-- Intro with photo placeholder -->
        <div
            class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-10 sm:gap-14 items-start mb-14"
        >
            <!-- Photo slot -->
            <div class="relative shrink-0 slide-in-left">
                <!-- Blurred border effect -->
                <div
                    class="absolute -inset-2 rounded-xl"
                    style="background: radial-gradient(ellipse at center, var(--accent-warm) 0%, transparent 70%); opacity: 0.15; filter: blur(16px);"
                >
                </div>
                <!-- Image container -->
                <div
                    class="relative rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-rule"
                    style="box-shadow: 0 8px 32px rgba(0,0,0,0.4);"
                >
                    <img
                        src="/profile.webp"
                        alt="Dr Fazeen Nasser"
                        class="w-44 h-52 sm:w-52 sm:h-60 object-cover"
                    />
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Intro text -->
            <div class="pt-1">
                <p class="section-label mb-3 fade-up" data-stagger="1">Dr Fazeen Nasser</p>
                <h1
                    class="text-[2rem] font-semibold tracking-tight text-fg leading-tight mb-5 fade-up-hero"
                    data-stagger="2"
                >
                    About
                </h1>
                <p class="text-[1.0625rem] text-fg-muted leading-[1.8] fade-up" data-stagger="3">
                    Emergency medicine clinician in East London. I also build
                    clinical AI products.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[1.0625rem] text-fg-muted leading-[1.8] mt-4 fade-up" data-stagger="4">
                    The two things are connected — everything I&apos;ve built started
                    as a problem I saw on shift.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <article class="prose section-enter">
            <h2>The work</h2>

            <p>
                I trained as a doctor in India, graduating from Kasturba Medical
                College in Manipal in 2019. I joined the medical operations and
                product team at DailyRounds/Marrow in Bengaluru, where I spent
                two and a half years helping scale India's leading medical
                education platform from an early-stage startup to over half a
                million users. I led a cross-functional team of twenty medical
                editors, designed the flagship "Pearls" feature, and did the
                unglamorous day-to-day work of translating educational needs
                into product requirements.
            </p>

            <p>
                Between 2022 and 2023 I ran a small family practice in Kerala.
                It was paper-based when I arrived. I partnered with a
                fintech-backed EHR startup to install and configure a digital
                record system; within weeks the clinic was running on software
                that our staff actively preferred to the old ledgers. That
                experience — being the only person in a resource-limited clinic
                who understood both the medicine and the technology — shaped how
                I think about health-tech deployment.
            </p>

            <p>
                I moved to London in late 2023 to practise emergency medicine at
                Whipps Cross Hospital as part of Barts Health NHS Trust. I'm
                currently an ST3-equivalent trust-grade doctor in a busy adult
                A&E, covering the full range of undifferentiated presentations
                across resus, majors, and ambulatory care. I co-lead a
                departmental quality improvement project on mental health
                pathway compliance and I teach medical students and foundation
                doctors on shift.
            </p>

            <h2>The building</h2>

            <p>
                Alongside clinical work, I build things. Most of them clinical
                AI.
            </p>

            <p>
                I've been experimenting with machine learning for healthcare
                since 2018, when I trained a convolutional neural network in
                PyTorch to prioritise chest X-rays as a final-year student. In
                2020 I placed second at the MIT COVID-19 Hackathon with a team
                building AI triage tools. In 2022 I launched NeurallyMed — an
                AI-powered PLAB exam preparation platform — which was acquired
                in 2023.
            </p>

            <p>
                I'm a founding engineer at two sister ventures, <strong
                    ><a href="/work/peerr">Peerr.io</a></strong
                > and
                <strong><a href="/work/aiigent">Aiigent.io</a></strong>, working
                on secure, AI-powered tooling for clinical networking and
                workflow optimisations. On the side I build smaller things I
                need — an AI guidelines retrieval platform for the ED (<strong
                    ><a href="/work/aide">Aide</a></strong
                >), a fitness and nutrition assistant for myself (<strong
                    ><a href="/work/leanifi">Leanifi</a></strong
                >), a study tool I built while sitting the MSRA (<strong
                    ><a href="https://msra.uk">msra.uk</a></strong
                >), a project microsite for the QIP I'm running at Whipps (<strong
                    ><a href="https://qip.fazeen.dev">qip.fazeen.dev</a></strong
                >). Some of these turn into products. Some stay personal tools.
                All of them start with a problem I saw on a shift.
            </p>

            <h2>What I care about</h2>

            <p>
                Most clinical AI projects fail not because the model is weak but
                because the implementation is weak. Poor workflow integration,
                weak governance, unclear accountability, thin evaluation. I want
                to do the opposite — ship things, evaluate them properly, write
                down what worked and what didn't so other people don't have to
                learn the same lessons from scratch.
            </p>

            <p>That's the thread.</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Available for collaborations in clinical AI deployment, digital
                health product consulting, and speaking on clinician-led
                technology development. <a href="/contact">Contact me</a>.
            </p>
        </article>
    </div>
</BaseLayout>
